-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE "Requirements" "System Requirements..."
@PREV "Download"

@{code}@{jcenter}@{fg shine}System Requirements...@{fg text}
@{jleft}
@{body}Since this archive requires DOpus5, you must have the minimum requirements as
stated in the DOpus5 manual: KickStart 2.04 or higher, 1 Meg RAM, and a Hard Drive.
However, a recommended configuration@{b}°@{ub} includes 4 Meg RAM and at least a 68030.
@{par}
@{par}@{b}°@{ub}Recommendation by Amiga Computing's Frank Nord - Issue 88, page 33.
@{par} See @{"DOpus5 Review" LINK "Review"}.

@ENDNODE

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE "Installation" "Installation"

@{code}@{jcenter}@{fg shine}Installation@{fg text}
@{jleft}
@{body}If anyone thinks that this archive requires an installation script then mail
me. I think most people would actually prefer to install this stuff themselves.
@{par}
@{par}All you need to do is copy this stuff where you want it. One recommendation,
however would be to rename the images drawer in DOpus5: to something else and
then copy the included images drawers into DOpus5: (since this is where DOpus
looks for icons be default).
@{par}
@{par}If the brushes and pictures are not compliant with your palette then you will
want to use @{"DIF" LINK "DIF"} (possibly in conjunction with @{"PaletteShove" LINK "PS"}) - both programs and
their respective documentation are included in this archive in @{"c (dir)" LINK "C"}.
@{par}
@{par}As for the @{"pictures and the guide" LINK "DownLoad"}, you can delete them when you're done with
them (although you might like to hang on to the @{"Buttons_Template" SYSTEM "sys:utilities/multiview button_template"} which will
serve as a good template for drawing your own icons and an index when you are
not sure which icon to pick).

@ENDNODE

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE "HintsTips" "Hints & Tips & HELP!"
@NEXT "Author"

@{code}@{jcenter}@{fg shine}Hints & Tips & HELP!@{fg text}
@{jleft}
 · If you decide to use the included toolbar icons, it is a good idea to delete
   or rename the @{b}default images drawer@{ub} in @{b}DOpus5:@{ub}. Then copy the @{"Images" LINK "Images"} drawer
   included in this archive into your @{b}DOpus5:@{ub} directory (since this is where
   DOpus looks for images by default).

 · If you want to make a drive bank (similar to DOpus4) you can use a button
   bank with the @{b}ScanDir@{ub} command (see my @{"DOpusScreen.pic" SYSTEM "sys:utilities/multiview dopusscreen.pic"}).
   (Or, even better, use @{"CDOpus" LINK "LeoASM"} :-)
@{fg text}
 · Is it possible to have drive icons on the DOpus screen which do not
   necessarily exist on WorkBench? For instance, for an assign?
@{fg fill}
   -> Answered by @{"Leo Davidson" LINK "Author"}: You can @{b}leave out@{ub} any directory, so long as
      it has an ICON. Directories left out on the DOpus screen are @{b}NOT@{ub} left
      out on the Workbench (unless you also leave them out on the Workbench).
      BUT, you can't leave things out which do not have an icon.
@{fg text}
 · Is everyone having the same problems I am with snapshoting icons in DOpus..
   wherever you snapshot the windows in DOpus is where they end up on the
   workbench? Am I doing something wrong?
@{fg fill}
   -> Answered by @{"Leo Davidson" LINK "Author"}: Yes, there is currently no way around this :(
@{fg text}
 · What happened to the SWAPDIR and COPYDIR commands? Is there a way to
   impliment this through other commands (to operate on the source and the
   destination)?
@{fg fill}
   -> Answered by @{"Greg Perry" LINK "LeoD5PM_OrderInfo"}: the COPYWIN command may be envoked via ARexx.
      OR, even better, @{"DOpusFuncs" LINK "LeoASM"} provides SWAPDIR, COPYDIR and many other
      extra functions.
@{fg text}
 · Can you save the prefs so that the clock remains ON?
@{fg fill}
   -> Answered by @{"Leo Davidson" LINK "Author"}: Yes, but you must quit DOpus for the changes to
      remain in effect.
@{fg text}
 · How do you replace the cycle gadget in the ToolBarLister?
@{fg fill}
   -> Answered by @{"Leo Davidson" LINK "Author"}: See @{"Images" LINK "Images"} - at the bottom of the page, there
      is a note on how to replace the cycle gadget.
@{fg text}
 · Here are a couple of great tips from @{"Leo Davidson" LINK "Author"}:
   @{"How to add an LHA destination-path file-requester to a button (or menu)    " LINK "LHADest"}
   @{"An LHA button (or menu) which creates seperate directories for each archive" LINK "LHADir"}

 · Why do all screens remap whenever you change resolution (i.e. in paint
   programs) whenever DOpus is running? For instance if you change the page
   size in OpalPaint while the DOpus window is open then Workbench remaps it's
   screen, however if DOpus is iconified this doesn't happen (it is very
   annoying and it slows things down!).

 · In order to play @{b}The Settlers@{ub} (© BlueByte), you must kill DOpus or your
   machine goes Balistic (WHY, does it have something to do will the PAL mode?)

 · Where do you put the PublicScreen name for the {Qs} delimiter? I've tried:
   command {@{b}Qs@{ub}Workbench}
   command {@{b}Qs@{ub}"Workbench"}
   command {@{b}Qs@{ub}}Workbench
   command {@{b}Qs@{ub}}"Workbench"
   but none of these work...help!
@{fg fill}
   -> Answered by @{"Leo Davidson" LINK "Author"}: {Qs} is like the {Qp} command. It inserts
      DOpus's public screen name into the command string. It doesn't check if
      a named public screen exists or anything like that.

      @{b}NOTE@{ub}: You can't use {} sequenses in "command" type commands. This is a
            common misconception.
@{fg text}
 · Has anyone ever had any luck installing @{"LhaDir.DOpus5" LINK "EVLhaDir"} and getting it to work
   on the first try? I found this utility quite difficult to get going - maybe
   it is just me, but for those of you who are having trouble, I've provided
   @{"some hints to help you install LhaDir.DOpus5" LINK "InstallLhaDir"}.

 · If you have @{"CheckGuide" LINK "CheckGuide"} you can save yourself some time by adding it to DOpus
   as either a Button or User-Menu item (@{"click for an example of how to do it" LINK "DCG"}).

 · Check out @{"Jonathon Potter's tip on how to add DIF to DOpus" LINK "DIF"}.

 · Check out this great tip on @{"How to get DOpus to Parse commands" LINK "Parse"}.

 · Need some help configuring DOpus5's @{"FileTypes" LINK "Filetype"} ?

 · Do you hate having to activate a window before you can use RMB-functions
   such as scrolling or selecting alternative buttons? There are two ways you
   can get around this: 1) either run a "Sun-Mouse" autopoint program to make
   the window under the mouse active, or 2) run a RMB-Active program. A lot of
   people do not like Sun-Mouse, and it seems many people have never really
   thought about RMB-Active. With RMB-Active you can click on windows with the
   right (and middle) mouse button and the result is the same as if you had
   clicked the LMB (ie. the window becomes active!). No more having to left-
   click on a non-gadget part of the window before using those RMB/MMB
   functions! YAK, @{"MCP" LINK "MCP"} and MagicCX, amoung others, will do a very good job if
   you want either Sun-Mouse or RMB-active. Grab them and give it a try!

 · Did you know that the pull-down menus in DOpus5 can extend to two columns if
   you add enough entries to reach the button of the screen? Don't be afraid to
   add more and more!

 · Here is a great tip on how to use DOpus5 and @{"ITools (by Tobias Ferber)" LINK "IM"} to
   @{"Convert Brushes into Icons" LINK "CBI"} (as was done for the Image dirs in this archive).

 · Since this archive comes with both icon and brush versions of each button,
   @{"Jonathon Potter" LINK "Thanks"} points out the following:  Icons are loaded using the
   GetDiskObject() function, which loads the whole icon (gadget structure,
   image structure, tooltypes, etc) as well as the image data. Loading brushes
   just loads the image data itself. So, although DOpus will recognize EITHER
   icons or brushes, it is most economical to use brushes for Lister Buttons!

 · Don't you hate that when you double-click on a 2 Meg file and have to wait
   forever while DOpus reads the whole thing into SmartRead because it did not
   recognize it?
@{fg fill}
   -> Read this great hint how to add @{"Selective Smartreading" LINK "Smart"} to your DOpus.
@{fg text}
 · Do you wish you had more control over the configuration of the DOpus output
   window?
@{fg fill}
   -> Here is a simple kludge for @{"Configuring DOpus' Output Window" LINK "COW"}.
@{fg text}
 · The Index of this archive was created using @{"AGIX © Ralph Seichter" LINK "AGIX"}.
   See @{"How to create a user-defined function to call AGIX" LINK "AGIXfunc"}.

 If you have answers for any of these @{"I'd love to hear from you" LINK "Author"}. Or if you have
 something which you would like to share with others, contact @{"me" LINK "Author"} and I'll
 include it in this section.

@{fg shine}@{b}All Users of DOpus5@{ub}: The patch for DOpus5.11 is now on Aminet (Dopus511.lha)!!
Also OpusFTP.lha (FTP module for DOpus5) is now available on Aminet! @{fg text}

@ENDNODE


@NODE "LHADest" "Adding LHA with a destination file requester"
@PREV "LHADest"
@TOC "HintsTips"

@{code}@{jcenter}@{fg shine}How to add an LHA destination-path file-requester to a button (or menu) @{fg text}
@{jleft}
@{body}To add an LHA command to DOpus with a destination file requester use the
following to define either a button, a menu item or a gadget:
@{par}@{code}
 TYPE:      COMMAND:
 @{b}------------------------------------------------------------------------------ @{ub}@{fg fill}
 @{b}AmigaDOS@{ub} - FailAt 21
 @{b}AmigaDOS@{ub} - sys:c/RequestFile DRAWER={d} PATTERN=#?.(LHA|LZH) NOICONS @{b}@{fg shine}-> @{ub}@{fg fill}
            PUBSCREEN=DOPUS.1 SAVEMODE >PIPE:LHA_{Qp}
 @{b}AmigaDOS@{ub} - IF FAIL
 @{b}AmigaDOS@{ub} - QUIT
 @{b}AmigaDOS@{ub} - ENDIF
 @{b}AmigaDOS@{ub} - sys:c/LHA  -r -x u "`Type PIPE:LHA_{Qp}`" {O}@{fg text}
 @{b}------------------------------------------------------------------------------ @{ub}

Check the following flags:

 @{fg fill}· CD source
 · Output to window
 · Window close button@{fg text}

@{b}NOTE:@{ub} Make sure you change the @{b}sys:c/@{ub} in the last command line to point to
      the path where @{b}Lha@{ub} can be found on @{i}your@{ui} machine.

      the @{fg shine}@{b}->@{fg text}@{ub} means @{b}continued on the next line@{ub}; however, you would @{b}type this
      all on one line@{ub}.

      the @{b}RequestFile@{ub} command comes with OS3.x.

@ENDNODE


@NODE "LHADir" "An LHA button (or menu) which creates seperate dirs for each archive"
@TOC "HintsTips"

@{code}@{jcenter}@{fg shine}An LHA button (or menu) which creates seperate directories for each archive @{fg text}
@{jleft}
 TYPE:      COMMAND:
 @{b}------------------------------------------------------------------------------ @{ub}@{fg fill}
 @{b}AmigaDOS@{ub} - sys:c/LHA -M x {fu} {o-}/@{fg text}
 @{b}------------------------------------------------------------------------------ @{ub}

Check the following flags:

 @{fg fill}· Output to window
 · Window close button
 · CD destination@{fg text}

@{b}NOTE:@{ub} Make sure you change the @{b}sys:c/@{ub} to point to where the Lha command
      can be found on @{i}your@{ui} machine.

@ENDNODE


@NODE "InstallLhaDir" "Some hints to help you install LhaDir.DOpus5"
@TOC "HintsTips"

@{code}@{jcenter}@{fg shine}Some hints to help you install LhaDir.DOpus5@{fg text}
@{jleft}
 -> Make sure you edit the header in each script to suit your own machine (ie
    you may have to change the @{b}LhaCommand =@{ub} from sys:c/Lha to Work:Arc/Lha
    or something like that).

 -> Make sure you add the following lines to your startup-sequence (or user-
    startup):
              @{fg shine}sys:system/rexxmast >nil:
              c:runback >NIL: sys:rexxc/RX DOpus5:ARexx/LhaHandler.rexx
              c:path sys:Rexxc add@{fg text}

    You may also wish to add @{fg shine}c:resident c:Lha FORCE@{fg text} to speed things up.

    Remember, however, that your paths may be different!

 -> Make sure that you select the @{b}ARexx@{ub} command Function Editor cycle gadget
    and that every command (which you wish to pass to LhaDir.DOpus5) calls
    LhaDir.DOpus5 (ie. DOpus5:ARexx/LhaDir.DOpus5 @{b}MakeDir@{ub} {Qp}).

 -> If you still can't get things to work, select the @{b}Output to Reader@{ub} option
    in the function editor to find out what is going on (this is useful for
    debugging at any time and not just for LhaDir.DOpus5).

 -> As a recommendation, I suggest you make a seperate LHA_COMMANDS button
    bank, since LhaDir.DOpus5 slows regular functions down and sometimes it
    does some weird things like prompt you for a destination dir when copying
    files!? See my @{"DOpusScreen.pic" LINK "DownLoad"} for an example.

@ENDNODE


@NODE "DCG" "How to add CheckGuide to DOpus"
@TOC "HintsTips"

@{code}@{jcenter}@{fg shine}How to add CheckGuide to DOpus@{fg text}
@{jleft}
 TYPE:      COMMAND:
 @{b}------------------------------------------------------------------------------ @{ub}@{fg fill}
 @{b}AmigaDOS@{ub} - Work:Utilities/CheckGuide {F}
 @{fg text}@{b}------------------------------------------------------------------------------ @{ub}

Check the following flags:

 @{fg fill}· CD source
 · Output to reader
 · Do all files@{fg text}

 @{b}NOTE:@{ub} Do not forget to change @{b}Work:Utilities/@{ub} to the proper source on @{b}your @{ub}
       drive.

@ENDNODE


@NODE "Parse" "Parse Command"
@TOC "HintsTips"

@{code}@{jcenter}@{fg shine}"Parse" Command@{fg text}
@{jleft}
@{body}This function can be used when you want to run a program for which you have not
set up a button, but which requires arguments. It can also be used for running
a program on the selected file(s) (ie. basically for when you are too lazy to
open a shell window!).
@{par}
@{par}For example, if you select a file called @{b}Widget.Nad@{ub} and use Parse, you will be
asked for a string to go before and after it. This will be built into a
command-line which is then executed. Let's say that @{b}Widget.Nad@{ub} was a picture
you wanted to show with @{b}ViewTek@{ub}, and you wanted to use ViewTek's @{b}NoBusy@{ub} option,
you would enter @{b}Viewtek@{ub} in the first requester and @{b}NoBusy@{ub} in the second one.
@{b}Note@{ub} that you are not limited to single word answers - this is just an
example:
@{par}
@{par}@{fg fill}Viewtek Widget.Nad NoBusy@{fg text}
@{par}
@{par}...would then be executed, and the picture displayed.
@{par}
@{par}As another example, say that you have downloaded a new program called @{b}NadBuster @{ub}
which requires a shell-argument @{b}Config@{ub} to tell it where its config file is. Let
us also say you have created and saved this config as @{b}RAM:NadBuster.config@{ub}. All
you have to do is select the @{b}NadBuster@{ub} program file, click on Parse, leave the
first requester blank (just hit RETURN), and type @{b}Config RAM:NadBuster.config@{ub}.
@{par}
@{par}@{fg fill}NadBuster RAM:NadBuster.config@{fg text} would then be run.
@{par}
@{par}OK, I hope you get the idea now. Want to know how many lines the actual
function which took so long to describe is?...  Just one @{fg shine}@{b}:@{fg text}@{ub}-).
@{par}(It is not complicated - just very usefull!).
@{par}@{code}
 TYPE:      COMMAND:
 @{b}------------------------------------------------------------------------------ @{ub}@{fg fill}
 @{b}AmigaDOS@{ub} - {RsEnter String To Preceed Filename} {o} {RsEnter String To @{b}@{fg shine}-> @{ub}@{fg fill}
            Follow Filename}@{fg text}
 @{b}------------------------------------------------------------------------------ @{ub}

Check the following flags:

 @{fg fill}· CD source
 · Do all files
 · No file quote  (** Optional, sometimes you'll want this off **)
 · Output to window
 · Window close button@{fg text}

@{b}NOTE:@{ub} the @{fg shine}@{b}->@{fg text}@{ub} means @{b}continued on the next line@{ub}; however, you would @{b}type this
      all on one line@{ub}.

@ENDNODE


@NODE "FileType" "FileType"
@TOC "HintsTips"

@{code}@{jcenter}@{fg shine}FileType Priorities@{fg text}
@{jleft}
@{body}Special thanks to @{"Jonathan Potter" LINK "Thanks"} for helping me out with some of the details
used in this section.
@{par}
@{par}Usually, you will want all of your filetypes to have a priority of zero.
However, the filetype priorities become very useful when you have one filetype
which is a subset of another. For example, 24-bit IFF-pictures are a subset of
regular IFF-pictures, and while only a 24-bit picture will match the first
type, ANY type of IFF-picture will match the second.
@{par}
@{par}I've got about 8 different picture viewers on my harddrive. On my setup, PPShow
seems to be the best one for showing 24-bit IFF-pictures, but for other things
I prefer to use Viewtek. Obviously I've set the 24-bit IFF-picture filetype to
use PPShow, and the IFF-picture datatype to use Viewtek, but this isn't enough.
DOpus will act on the first filetype which matches the file, so you have to do
something to ensure that a 24-bit IFF-picture isn't matched by the IFF-picture
filetype! This is simple to do - just put the 24-bit filetype at a higher
priority. My IFF-picture filetype is at priority 0 (zero), so I set the 24-bit
filetype to 1 (one), and everything works fine.
@{par}
@{par}Similarily, I have a filetype which matches ASCII text and extracts binary data
from the file in one of two ways: UUEncoded data via drag-n-drop and User2
(which is "Unpack" on my setup). Because a UUEncoded file would match the
standard ASCII filetype, I set the UUEncoded filetype to a higher priority.
@{par}@{code}@{jcenter}@{u}                                                                               @{uu}

@{b}Undocumented Feature@{ub}
@{jleft}
@{body}DOpus5 has some internal filetypes which exist even if you were to delete ALL
the @{b}DOpus5:Filetypes/@{ub} files.
@{par}
@{par}Essentially there are two sets of filetypes: those set at priority -125, which
display pictures, play sounds, etc., and the "last-resort" filetype at priority
-127, which just calls @{b}SmartRead@{ub} if a file was @{b}Double-Clicked@{ub}, and @{b}Copy@{ub} if it
was @{b}Drag-n-Drop@{ub}ped.
@{par}
@{par}@{b}NOTE@{ub}: The "last-restort" will only get used if NO filetype matches are found
@{par}      (ie. if none of the -125 filetypes are matched).
@{par}
@{par}The filetype priority -126 is left unused so that you may create a filetype
which will match ALL files (MatchName #?) and define an action (ie. for Double-
Click, User1, Drag-n-Drop, etc) you wish preformed if absolutely none of the
other filetypes match the selected file.
@{par}
@{par}@{b}NOTE@{ub}: In order to have an action preformed by the filetype priorities greater
@{par}      than -126 (ie -125 and up), you must have actions defined for them.
@{par}
@{par}Since the priority -127 filetype actions for Double-Click and Drag-n-Drop are
what most people would want as the "last-resort," your -126 filetype probably
won't define anything for those actions. However, the -127 filetype has nothing
defined for the @{b}UserX@{ub} actions. This means that if you do @{b}User1@{ub} on a file and
none of the filetypes match the file (AND you have a User1 action defined),
absolutely nothing will happen. So to MAKE something happen by @{i}default@{ui} on the
@{b}UserX@{ub} actions, you may define them in your -126 filetype.
@{par}@{code}
@{b}FINAL NOTE@{ub}: You DO NOT have to define every action for each filetype. For
            example, my @{i}default@{ui} filetype has the Drag-n-Drop action defined as
            the internal @{b}Copy@{ub} command. If you are editing a filetype, say for
            IFF-pictures, and you want them to be copied when Drag-n-Drop, you
            can leave the Drag-n-Drop action blank because the pictures will
            drop through the IFF-picture filetype and be caught by your @{i}default @{ui}
            filetype (assuming they don't match another filetype on the way, of
            course!).
@{jcenter}@{u}                                                                               @{uu}
@{jleft}
@{body}I know this stuff sounds complicated (try explaining it @{fg shine}@{b}:@{ub}@{fg text}), but if you require
help/clarification then feel free to contact @{"one of us" LINK "Author"}.
@{par}
@{par}Also see @{"Selective SmartReading" LINK "Smart"}.

@ENDNODE


@NODE "CBI" "Convert Icons into Brushes"
@TOC "HintsTips"

@{code}@{jcenter}@{fg shine}Convert Icons into Brushes@{fg text}
@{jleft}
 TYPE:      COMMAND:
 @{b}------------------------------------------------------------------------------ @{ub}@{fg fill}
 @{b}AmigaDOS@{ub} - Sys:c/IM FROM {fu} TO {o}@{fg text}
 @{b}------------------------------------------------------------------------------ @{ub}

Check the following flags:

 @{fg fill}· CD destination
 · Do all files
 · Rescan destination
 · (Run asynchronously)@{fg text} - optional

@{b}NOTE:@{ub} Make sure you change the @{b}sys:c/@{ub} to point to where the @{"IM" LINK "IM"} command
      can be found on @{i}your@{ui} machine.

@ENDNODE


@NODE "Smart" "Selective Smartreading"
@TOC "HintsTips"

@{code}@{jcenter}@{fg shine}Selective Smartreading@{fg text}
@{jleft}
@{body}If you would like to be asked whether or not to do a @{b}SmartRead@{ub} on files of an
unrecognised filetype, install the following command as the @{b}Double-Click@{ub} action
of your "Default" filetype (see @{"Filetype Priorities" LINK "FileType"} for a description of how to
setup a "Default" filetype - Priority -126, Matchname #?):
@{par}@{code}
 TYPE:      COMMAND:
 @{b}------------------------------------------------------------------------------ @{ub}@{fg fill}
 @{b}Command @{ub} - Confirm Unknown filetype, view with SmartRead?
 @{b}Command @{ub} - SmartRead@{fg text}
 @{b}------------------------------------------------------------------------------ @{ub}

Or, alternatively, you could use:

 TYPE:      COMMAND:
 @{b}------------------------------------------------------------------------------ @{ub}@{fg fill}
 @{b}Command @{ub} - Confirm Unknown filetype, view with MultiView?
 @{b}AmigaDOS@{ub} - MultiView {f} SCREEN@{fg text}
 @{b}------------------------------------------------------------------------------ @{ub}

@{body}If you give a negative response to the requester you will not have to waste
time waiting for SmartRead/Multiview to display the file if you don't want to
see it.
@{par}
@{par}Also, just so that DOpus does not ask you wether you want to read a file which
is obviously a text file (ie. #?.doc, #?.txt), you may wish to add another
filetype to handle them. For example, define a new filetype called ASCII (or
whatever you like) which preforms the following for Double-Click:
@{par}@{code}
 TYPE:      COMMAND:
 @{b}------------------------------------------------------------------------------ @{ub}@{fg fill}
 @{b}Command @{ub} - Read@{fg text}
 @{b}------------------------------------------------------------------------------ @{ub}

and for @{b}Edit definition...@{ub} enter the following:

 @{fg fill}@{b}Name@{ub}: ASCII    @{b}ID@{ub}:   ASCII    @{b}Pri@{ub}:  0
 @{b}Match Name@{ub}  *.(txt|readme|displayme|doc|diz|list|rexx|dopus5) @{fg text}

@{b}NOTE@{ub}: You may add or remove as many of the identifiers as you like.

@{body}If you are using @{b}OS3@{ub} and have the @{b}ASCII datatype@{ub} installed, you can use this
definition @{i}instead @{ui}which will catch @{u}all@{uu} ASCII files, regardless of their
file extension:
@{par}
@{par} @{fg fill}@{b}Match DT ID@{ub}  ascii Text@{fg text}
@{par}

@ENDNODE


@NODE "COW" "Configuring the DOpus Output Window"
@TOC "HintsTips"

@{code}@{jcenter}@{fg shine}Configuring the DOpus Output Window@{fg text}
@{jleft}
@{body}The only things you are meant to be able to change about the output window are
its title and its dimensions. If you are running a shell such as KingCon, you
may want to take advantage of some of its extra features, and you can actually
do this quite easily with this simple kludge.
@{par}
@{par}Let's say you want to add the @{b}INACTIVE@{ub} option to DOpus5's output window, so
that when an output window opens it does not become the active window and steal
the input stream. (Often I start doing something else shortly after starting a
function which will take a long time, such as crunching some AmigaGuides - I
do not want the output window to become active while I'm typing into another
window, I just want to READ the output window).
@{par}
@{par}Go to @{b}Environment/Output_Window@{ub} and change the @{b}Title:@{ub} string gadget
to read something like:
@{par}
@{par}@{fg fill} Directory Opus Output/INACTIVE@{fg text}
@{par}
@{par}Of course, you can specify any other options you might like, such as a special
buffer size, or no-history/scroll-back buffer, etc.

@ENDNODE


@NODE "AGIXfunc" "How to create a user-defined function to call AGIX"
@NEXT "AGIXfunc"
@TOC "HintsTips"

@{code}@{jcenter}@{fg shine}How to create a user-defined function to call AGIX@{fg text}
@{jleft}
 TYPE:      COMMAND:
 @{b}------------------------------------------------------------------------------ @{ub}@{fg fill}
 @{b}AmigaDOS@{ub} - sys:c/AGIX {f} >{RsEnter Index name}@{fg text}
 @{b}------------------------------------------------------------------------------ @{ub}

Check the following flags:

 @{fg fill}· CD destination
 · CD destination
 · Rescan dest
 · (Run asynchronously)@{fg text} - optional

@{b}NOTE:@{ub} Make sure you change the @{b}sys:c/@{ub} to point to where the @{"AGIX" LINK "AGIX"} command
      can be found on @{i}your@{ui} machine.

@ENDNODE

